aa(lp51
VI'm particularly interested in how you can't rely on your own perception.
p52
aVThis is Jane Smith and Jo Bloggs, for instance,
p53
aVbut you think it's Camilla and the Queen,
p54
aVand I'm fascinated how what you think is real isn't necessarily real.
p55
aVAnd the camera can lie,
p56
aVand it makes it very, very easy
p57
aVwith the mass bombardment of imagery to tell untruths.
p58
aVSo, I continued to work on this project of how photography seduces us
p59
aVand is more interesting to look at than the actual real subject matter.
p60
aVAnd at the same time, it removes us from the real subject matter,
p61
aa(lp62
Vand this acts as a sort of titillating thing.
p63
aVSo, the photograph becomes this teaser and incites desire and voyeurism;
p64
aVwhat you can't have, you want more.
p65
aVIn the photograph, the real subject doesn't exist
p66
aVso it makes you want that person more.
p67
aVAnd that is the way, I think, that celebrity magazines work now:
p68
aVthe more pictures you see of these celebrities,
p69
aVthe more you feel you know them,
p70
aVbut you don't know them
p71
aVand you want to know them further.
p72
